In [ ]:
# return Practice vertex attribute, assign to color

def generate_color_map(node_attributes):
    color_map = []
    n_colors = len(set(node_attributes.values()))
    palette = sns.color_palette("hls", n_colors)
    palette=dict(zip(set(node_attributes.values()), palette))
    for value in node_attributes.values():
        color_map.append(palette[value])
    return color_map

# https://pysal.org/spreg/notebooks/GM_Lag_example.html
import libpysal
from spreg import GM_Lag
from libpysal.weights import W
In [ ]:
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
# return age, practice, and office from networkx graph G as exogenous variables
age=nx.get_node_attributes(G, 'Age')
practice=nx.get_node_attributes(G, 'Practice')
office=nx.get_node_attributes(G, 'Office')
gender=nx.get_node_attributes(G, "Gender")
exog=pd.DataFrame({"age":age, "practice":practice, "office":office, "Gender":gender})
exog=pd.concat([exog["age"],pd.get_dummies(exog["practice"]).iloc[:,1].rename("practice"),exog["office"].isin([2,3]).astype(int),exog["Gender"].isin([2]).astype(int)],axis=1).values
exog[:,:]=StandardScaler().fit_transform(exog)

# return seniority from networkx graph G as endogenous variable
seniority=nx.get_node_attributes(G, 'Years')
endog=pd.Series(seniority).values.reshape(-1,1)
# endog[:,:]=StandardScaler().fit_transform(endog)
In [ ]:
# Now create the libpysal weights matrix
w = W({n:list(nx.all_neighbors(G,n)) for n in list(G.nodes())})
w.transform = 'r'
In [ ]:
# Create a GM_Lag model instance
model = GM_Lag(endog, exog, w=w, w_lags=6, slx_lags=6, name_y='years', name_x=['age', 'practice', 'office',"gender"], robust='white', spat_diag=True)

# Print out the summary of results
print(model.summary)
